    "comment": "Rationale: Fig.2: \"Arcadlin Inhibits the Adhesive Activity of N-Cadherin\"\nFig.3: \"Depolarization or Elevated cAMP Level Increases N-Cadherin Internalization through an Arcadlin-Dependent Pathway\"\nFig.5: \"Homophilic Interaction of Arcadlin Causes Internalization via the Activation of Arcadlin-TAO2β-p38 MAPK Signaling Pathway\"\nFig.7: \"The Arcadlin-TAO2β-p38 MAPK Pathway Mediates the Internalization of N-Cadherin\"\n[Fig.8: \"The Effects of Arcadlin on Dendritic Spine Density\"]\n\nN-Cadherin is a well established mediator of pre/post-synaptic adhesion. In this paper Arcadlin; PCDH8 is shown to not mediate adhesion itself, but to regulate the activity dependent internalization of N-cadherin, thereby affecting synapse organization (this paper) and synaptic transmission (see pmid:10383464).. Experimental description: - Tissues were from rat: \"Rat brain sections, cultured hippocampal neurons, ...\" and acad-/- mice (Fig.3, Fig.7, Fig.8)\n- Overexpressed Arcadlin; PCDH8 protein was of rat species: \"Cloning of Rat Arcadlin cDNA\" (traced back to pmid:10383464)",
